s-de-France, France":"Roye, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Département de l'Aisne, Picardie, France":"Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Aisne, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Coucy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Devon): nickname from Middle English <i>couch(e)</i> ‘hump, hunch’, used for a hunchback. In Cornwall and Devon it is usually pronounced as <i>Cooch</i>.","English (Cornwall and Devon): variant of   Gooch  .","English (Cornwall and Devon): from Middle English <i>coche</i>, <i>couche</i> ‘bed, couch, tablecloth’ (Old French <i>couche</i>, <i>culche</i>). It could have been a metonymic occupational name for someone who made such items or a nickname for a lazy individual. Alternatively, it could have been applied to someone who produced <i>couchwork</i>, a luxurious embroidery in which gold or silver thread and jewels were sewn into satin or silk robes."],"variants":[{"name":"Gooch","meanings":["English (East Anglia): from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Goche</i> (also found as <i>Joche</i>). It was current in East Anglia from the early 12th to the early 13th centuries as a variant of Anglo-Norman French <i>Go(s)ce</i>, <i>Jo(s)ce</i>, a pet form of Old French <i>Goscelin</i>.","English: alternatively, a nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>gouge</i> (from Latin <i>gobio</i>), the nominative form of Old French <i>goujon</i> (from Latin <i>gobionem</i>) ‘gudgeon’, perhaps for a gullible person.","Welsh: in southwestern England, possibly an Anglicized form of Welsh <i>coch</i>, <i>goch</i> ‘red(-haired)’, though the sound change is irregular. Compare   Gough  . It may also be a variant of Cornish and Welsh   Couch  , with the same meaning."]},{"name":"Gush","meanings":["English (Devon and Dorset): probably a variant of <b>Gudge</b>, itself a variant of   Couch   or   Gooch  ."]},{"name":"Coach","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Couch  .","Possibly also an Americanized form of French Canadian or French   Coache  ."]}]},{"name":"Odette","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine diminutive form of the Old French male name <i>Oda</i>, which is of Germanic origin . Although the original boy's name has dropped out of use, this feminine derivative has survived and has been in occasional use in the English-speaking world since the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Odette de Coucy was born in 1108, in Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Aisne, Picardie, France. She had at least 1 son with Alberic De Roye. She died in 1157, in Montdidier, Moselle, Grand Est, France, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1108–1157":"1108–1157","1100–1163":"1100–1163","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1190":"1190","1157":"1157","1100":"1100","1130":"1130","1163":"1163","15 janvier 1130":"15. jaanuar 1130","1108":"1108","Roye, Somme, Picardy, France":"Montdidier, Moselle, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa","Roye, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Roye, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Département de l'Aisne, Picardie, France":"Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Aisne, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1108–1157":"1108–1157","1100–1163":"1100–1163